<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
The problem here is that all forms of expression are being limited.<P>It used to be that kids had an outlet of some type for their aggression.  The concept that blowing things up on a computer screen reduces aggression is rot, and has proven to be so.  I have a teenage son that thinks playing violent games reduces his aggression, but it does just the opposite.<P>I don't blame the makers of violent material for the problem, just as I don't blame producers of pornography for the problems it causes, nor do I blame gambling casinos for the problems they cause.<P>The problem is that our society pushes a philosophy of 'freedom means you get to do what you want' instead of 'freedom gives you rights and responsibilities.'  Many children are not taught responsible behavior (by parents or schools) and don't learn what is important.<P>Vioent games, however, do lead those people who have greater dificulty discerning these things to have more trouble.  Death has little meaning, and consequences are few.  <P>I agree that it is the parent's fault, but it is important to recognize that there is influence at work.  Try to stop your child from doing some of these violent things.  Can't be done.  Best you can do is do your best to teach them.<P>--------------------<P>Josef - Servant of Balance
</FONT>
