Sometimes the lawsuit isn't about getting the money.  (Not talking about this case, but in general)<P>My sister-in-law died last November of complications with pregnancy.  The child died too.<P>For weeks before she died, she kept going to the doctor (at least 8 visits in 2 weeks.) for chest pain.  The doctor kept telling her it was normal and performed no tests.  She had extremely high blood pressure.  Two days before she died, she went into the hospital for the same reason.  Again, her doctor sent her home without tests.  She died because her Aorta split.  <P>Every other doctor we have talked to wondered why no tests were performed.  The medical review board clearly showed the doctor was at fault.  But since there was no 'intent to harm', no criminal action can be taken.<P>Our only resort is to sue the guy and hope that the insurance companies cancel his malpractice insurance.  He has shown no remorse.  His response at hte medical review, six months after she died was "Who was she again?  Oh, I don't recall how she died."<P>If I had an option, I would get pull the electric chair switch on him.  He doesn't deserve to be a doctor.  He murdered her and her child as surely as drunk drivers murder.  Only he shows no remorse and is not liable.  <P>I could understand if it happened with no warning, but this was not the case.  I hope her husband gets 100 Million.  Not for the money.  I want him out.<P>--------------------<P>Josef - Servant of Balance
